Singularity (your system) — hard definition

Goal:
Given a query q, construct a path of concepts P = (c_1, c_2, ..., c_n) that maximizes a connection score.

⸻

Core scoring function

You don’t need mystical language—you need something like:

S(P \mid q) = \alpha \cdot \sum_i \text{sim}(q, c_i)
+ \beta \cdot \sum_i \text{sim}(c_i, c_{i+1})
- \gamma \cdot \text{redundancy}(P)

This is where your system actually lives or dies.

S(P \mid q) = \alpha \sum_i \mathrm{sim}(q, c_i) + \beta \sum_i \mathrm{sim}(c_i, c_{i+1}) - \gamma , \mathrm{redundancy}(P)

⸻

Interpretation (no fluff)

* First term → relevance to the goal
* Second term → strength of connections (your key idea)
* Third term → penalty for looping / saying the same thing

If your “Singularity” is real, it should beat a baseline that only uses the first term.

